Issues.Body:
As browsers are supporting nesting CSS, I am steering away from SCSS. I used to use the following SCSS code to customize Bulma styles:
```scss
$primary: #b78e6c;
$radius: 2px;
$input-focus-box-shadow-size: 0 0 0 0;
$button-focus-box-shadow-size: 0 0 0 0;
$navbar-breakpoint: 600px;
$card-shadow: 0px 2px 1px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2),
  0px 1px 1px 0px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.14), 0px 1px 3px 0px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.12);

@import "https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/bulma@0.9.4/css/bulma.min.css";
```

Apparently these SCSS variables won't work with plain CSS. I wonder if there's any way I can customize Bulma styles with only CSS variables? Thanks.

Hi there, I'm using bulma version 0.9.4 and I've tried to create a dark theme (using SASS) for my website using the scheme variables for 'Dark mode'.
https://bulma.io/2019/10/15/light-dark-colors/

`$scheme: $white;
$scheme-main: $black;
$scheme-main-bis: $white-bis;
$scheme-main-ter: $white-ter;
$scheme-invert: $black;
$scheme-invert-bis: $black-bis;
$scheme-invert-ter: $black-ter;`

BUT not all colours have changed. There is still #fafafa within the table, the footer and the background of the (is-dark) navigation pulldown is still way to light and doesn't change. I've tried a bunch of variables, but it seems I can't change these parts.

Any idea what to do about it?

In fact - just invert light into dark (if it would work properly) looks aweful. Why is there no alternative to the standard light bulma colours for people who prefer dark modes on their websites? :(

This is about the Bulma **CSS framework** v0.9.4.

### Description

If any `<input...>` field does not validate (eg max, min etc) it gets a red border to indicate missing or wrong value. But it does not work for `<textarea...>` fields.

I was forced to add the following CSS to my project:

```
textarea:invalid {
    border: 1px solid rgb(235, 76, 36);
} 
```
